Subtitle of Senate Bill 620
TO PROVIDE A SAFETY VALVE AND APPEAL RIGHT FOR A MINOR DEFENDANT WHO
IS ALSO A VICTIM OF HUMAN TRAFFICKING; AND TO AMEND THE HUMAN
TRAFFICKING ACT OF 2013.
______________________________________________________________________
Amendment No. 1 to Senate Bill 620
Amend Senate Bill 620 as originally introduced:
Add Representative Beaty Jr. as a cosponsor of the bill
AND
Delete everything after the enacting clause and substitute the following:
"SECTION 1. DO NOT CODIFY. Legislative intent.
The General Assembly intends for courts to consider whether a minor has
been a victim of human trafficking before transferring a delinquency matter
to the criminal division of circuit court or imposing a sentence upon the
person.
SECTION 2. Arkansas Code § 5-2-210 is amended to read as follows:
5-2-210. Human trafficking — Affirmative defense.
(a) As used in this section,:
(1) "Nonviolent criminal offense" means a criminal offense that
does not constitute a violent crime as defined in § 16-90-1101; and
(2) “victim Victim of trafficking of persons” means a person who
has been subjected to trafficking of persons, § 5-18-103.
(b) It If a person is eighteen (18) years of age or older, it is an
affirmative defense to prosecution for an offense listed under subsection (c)
of this section if at the time a person engaged in the conduct charged to
